  <div class="ct">
  
<p>First, I'm part of the anti-war left. I organized numerous events against both wars, and continued to do so after Obama took office.<br />
I didn't vote for Obama believing he would quickly enact every policy I wanted or immediately end the war in Afghanistan. He made it clear during the campaign that he wouldn't. I supported Obama because he provided the OPPORTUNITY for change, not a guarantee of change. He seemed like someone who would respond when the grassroots built support around progressive goals.</p>
<p>I haven't been that disappointed in Obama because I didn't expect him to deliver change on a platter. He did warn us that he wouldn't. I've been far, far more disappointed in activists who apparently feel that whining about Obama and repeating "where's the hope and change?!!?!" cliches is an acceptable substitute for actual organizing. We were supposed to push Congress and Obama, but there was less organized pushing and more cynical pissing and moaning.</p>
<p>No, Obama's policies are not worse than Bush's. He curtailed the worst practices. I don't enjoy exaggeration. Yes, Obama does need to be pushed to do more. I bet he'll do more once the left builds support for better policies. That's our job.</p>
<p>Getting Congress to repeal the AUMF is an organizing opportunity but I'm afraid the netroots won't be up to the task. Too many want a President Santa Claus to do it for them.</p>

