<li id="c196">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50276749">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Nine US bases in Afghanistan after 2014</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1211456/50276749#c196?mode=alone;showrate=1#c196">6+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:50679">Superpole</a>, <a href="/user/uid:306084">Bisbonian</a>, <a href="/user/uid:57293">lotlizard</a>, <a href="/user/uid:98722">aliasalias</a>, <a href="/user/uid:161474">Susan from 29</a>, <a href="/user/uid:3312">Odysseus</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>have been negotiated. &nbsp;I don't know how many of those are near Iran, but it has been reported that a number of them are.</p>
<p>Thousands, maybe more than ten thousand troops will be kept in Afghanistan, and though the "noncombat" language is being used, that will almost certainly turn out not to be true because it's also being reported that Special Ops troops will be there and will be busy and while their mission might be defined as "training" they will definitely be engaged in combat.</p>
<p>The arrangement between our military and the governments of other countries is such that we're training special operations commando type troops in their countries, and working together with them to build forces. This is in addition to the "regular" armies in these countries, especially in Afghanistan. &nbsp;We're still learning about what our CIA paramilitary is doing there, and about their actions and JSOC actions.</p>
<p>We did similar things in Iraq and in recent months those activities in Iraq have increased, not decreased. &nbsp;We're also ramping up in Africa. &nbsp;</p>
<p>The perpetual war is not ending, it's just morphing. &nbsp;There are reasons for changing or repealing the AUMF, and ways to do it so that it won't mean much of anything to repeal it. &nbsp;While Obama is talking about ending the perpetual war, his Pentagon is also talking about how it might continue for 10-20 years. &nbsp;They are, presumably, talking about the Dirty Wars led by JSOC and intelligence agencies. There is no end in sight for those, and it could be argued that the dirty wars are creating more terrorists than they are killing. &nbsp;Obama talks about "associated forces" and also listen for other words like that, including the word "adherents" . &nbsp;The term "associated forces" is not in the original AUMF. The original AUMF only refers to the people who were involved in 9/11 or sheltered them. &nbsp;That is a problem for Obama because in order to wage his war wherever he wants (which is what he's doing) he needs that vague "associated forces" language. &nbsp;</p>
<p>"Associated forces" language is in the other AUMF that a lot of people forget about. The AUMF for war in Iraq, and there is no reason for that AUMF to still be in place. &nbsp;Obama should have asked for it to be repealed as soon as the photo op of the last combat troops leaving Iraq was finished. But he did not, and in fact he opposed the repeal of the Iraq AUMF because there is language in it that's critical for continuing business as usual. When Rand Paul, Wyden, Merkely and some others tried to repeal it more than a year ago, Obama did not want that. &nbsp;</p>
<p>So the "repeal" of the AUMF that Obama talks about is more likely to be a new authorization, not tied to 9/11 and one that states that he can wage the dirty wars anywhere and can kill anyone who he decides is a threat to the US, or anyone "associated" to them. &nbsp;Basically, this is what he's doing now but it's being done with a patchwork of laws and assumptions about what his Article 2 powers are. &nbsp;He's cleaning up the laws, giving himself unprecedented war powers for himself and future executives. &nbsp;And now he's shown us that he's going to do it under the auspices of ending the Forever War when in reality he's expanding his war powers and making them permanent, as long as Congress will agree to it, and there's no reason to doubt that they will limit him in any way since they have completely abdicated their Constitutional powers in matters of war.</p>

  </div>
